ay" title=3D"Radioactive decay">radioactivity</a> in the <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units" title=3D"Internationa=
l System of Units">International System of Units</a> (SI). One becquerel is=
 defined as an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Activity_(radioacti=
vity)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Activity (radioactivity)">activity</a=
> of one per <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Second" title=3D"Seco=
nd">second</a>, on average, for aperiodic activity events referred to a <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radionuclide" title=3D"Radionuclide">=
radionuclide</a>. For applications relating to human health this is a small=
 quantity,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Becquerel#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SI_multiple" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"SI multi=
ple">SI multiples</a> of the unit are commonly used.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Becquerel#cite=
_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The becquerel is named after <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Henri_Becquerel" title=3D"Henri Becquerel">Henri Becquerel</a>, who share=
d a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nobel_Prize_in_Physics" title=
=3D"Nobel Prize in Physics">Nobel Prize in Physics</a> with <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pierre_Curie" title=3D"Pierre Curie">Pierre</a> a=
nd <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marie_Curie" title=3D"Marie Cur=
ie">Marie  Curie</a> in 1903 for their work in discovering radioactivity.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-BIPMBecquerel_3-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Becquerel#cite_note-BIPMBecquerel-3"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Definition">Definition</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBecquerel&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Definition"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>1&nbsp;Bq =3D 1&nbsp;s<sup>=E2=88=921</sup>
</p><p>A special name was introduced for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Inverse_second" title=3D"Inverse second">reciprocal second</a> (=
s<sup>=E2=88=921</sup>) to represent radioactivity to avoid potentially dan=
gerous mistakes with prefixes. For example, 1&nbsp;=CE=BCs<sup>=E2=88=921</=
sup> would mean 10<sup>6</sup> disintegrations per second: <span class=3D"n=
owrap">(<span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"6994100000000000000=
=E2=99=A0"></span>10<sup>=E2=88=926</sup>&nbsp;s</span>)<sup>=E2=88=921</su=
p> =3D <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7006100000000000000=
=E2=99=A0"></span>10<sup>6</sup>&nbsp;s<sup>=E2=88=921</sup></span></span>,=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Allisy_4-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Becquerel#cite_note-Allisy-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> whereas 1&nbsp;=
=CE=BCBq would mean 1 disintegration per 1 million seconds: <span class=3D"=
nowrap">10<sup>=E2=80=936</sup> s<sup>=E2=80=931</sup></span>. Other names =
considered were <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hertz" title=3D"He=
rtz">hertz</a> (Hz), a special name already in use for the reciprocal secon=
d (for <i>periodic</i> events of any kind), and fourier (Fr; after <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_Fourier" title=3D"Joseph Fourier">=
Joseph Fourier</a>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Allisy_4-1" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Becquerel#cite_note-Allisy-4"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up> The hertz is now only used for periodic phenomena.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-B=
IPMtable3_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Becquerel#cite_note-BIPMtable3-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> While 1&nbsp;Hz replaces the =
deprecated term <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cycle_per_second" =
title=3D"Cycle per second">cycle per second</a>, 1 Bq refers to one event p=
er second on average for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aperiodic=
_frequency" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Aperiodic frequency">aperiodic</=
a> radioactive decays.
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gray_(unit)" title=3D"G=
ray (unit)">gray</a> (Gy) and the becquerel (Bq) were introduced in 1975.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-pmid_1251122_6-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Becquerel#cite_note-pmid_1251122-6"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Betwee=
n 1953 and 1975, absorbed dose was often measured with the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rad_(unit)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Rad (un=
it)">rad</a>. Decay activity was given with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Curie_(unit)" title=3D"Curie (unit)">curie</a> before 1946 an=
d often with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rutherford_(unit)=
" title=3D"Rutherford (unit)">rutherford</a> between 1946<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-pmid_17836457_7-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Becquerel#cite_note-pmid_17836457-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and 1975.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Unit_capitalization_and_pre=
fixes">Unit capitalization and prefixes</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection">=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBecquerel&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" ti=
tle=3D"Edit section: Unit capitalization and prefixes"><span>edit</span></a=
><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>As with every International System of Units (SI) unit named after a pers=
on, the first letter of its symbol is uppercase (Bq). However, when an SI u=
nit is spelled out in English, it should always begin with a lowercase lett=
er (becquerel)=E2=80=94except in a situation where any word in that positio=
n would be capitalized, such as at the beginning of a sentence or in materi=
al using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Title_case" title=3D"Titl=
e case">title case</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Becquerel#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Like any SI unit, Bq can be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/SI_prefix" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"SI prefix">prefixed</a>; commonl=
y used multiples are kBq (kilobecquerel, <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-=
sort-value=3D"7003100000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>10<sup>3</sup>&nbsp;Bq</=
span>), MBq (megabecquerel, <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D=
"7006100000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>10<sup>6</sup>&nbsp;Bq</span>, equiva=
lent to 1 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rutherford_(unit)" title=
=3D"Rutherford (unit)">rutherford</a>), GBq (gigabecquerel, <span class=3D"=
nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7009100000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>10<su=
p>9</sup>&nbsp;Bq</span>), TBq (terabecquerel, <span class=3D"nowrap"><span=
 data-sort-value=3D"7012100000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>10<sup>12</sup>&nb=
sp;Bq</span>), and PBq (petabecquerel, <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-so=
rt-value=3D"7015100000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>10<sup>15</sup>&nbsp;Bq</s=
pan>). Large prefixes are common for practical uses of the unit.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Examples">Examples</h2><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBecquerel&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Examples"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>For practical applications, 1&nbsp;Bq is a small unit. For example, ther=
e is roughly 0.017&nbsp;g of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Potas=
sium-40" title=3D"Potassium-40">potassium-40</a> in a typical human body, p=
roducing about 4,400 decays per second (Bq).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Becquerel#cite_note-9"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup>
</p><p>The activity of radioactive <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Americium" title=3D"Americium">americium</a> in a home <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smoke_detector" title=3D"Smoke detector">smoke detect=
or</a> is about 37&nbsp;kBq (1&nbsp;=CE=BCCi).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Becquerel#cite_note=
-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup>
</p><p>The global inventory of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Car=
bon-14" title=3D"Carbon-14">carbon-14</a> is estimated to be <span class=3D=
"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7018850000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>8.5<=
span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>=
18</sup>&nbsp;Bq</span> (8.5&nbsp;EBq, 8.5 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Exa" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Exa">exabecquerel</a>).<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Becquerel#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>These examples are useful for comparing the amount of activity of th=
ese radioactive materials, but should not be confused with the amount of ex=
posure to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ionizing_radiation" titl=
e=3D"Ionizing radiation">ionizing radiation</a> that these materials repres=
ent. The level of exposure and thus the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Absorbed_dose" title=3D"Absorbed dose">absorbed dose</a> received are=
 what should be considered when assessing the effects of ionizing radiation=
 on humans.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Relation_to_the_curie">Rela=
tion to the curie</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DBecquerel&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: R=
elation to the curie"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">]</span></span></div>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Radiation_units.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://=
upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/90/Radiation_units.svg/330px=
-Radiation_units.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"300" height=3D"150" c=
lass=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"512" data-file-height=3D"256"><=
/a><figcaption>Relation between some ionizing radiation units<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Becq=
uerel#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></figcaption></figure>
<p>The becquerel succeeded the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cur=
ie_(unit)" title=3D"Curie (unit)">curie</a> (Ci),<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Becquerel#cite_n=
ote-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> an older, non-SI unit of radioactivity based on the act=
ivity of 1&nbsp;gram of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radium-226=
" title=3D"Radium-226">radium-226</a>. The curie is defined as <span class=
=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7010370000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>3=
.7<span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em;">=C3=97</span>10<s=
up>10</sup>&nbsp;s<sup>=E2=88=921</sup></span>, or 37&nbsp;GBq.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-Allisy_4-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Becquerel#cite_note-Allisy-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Becquerel#cite_note=
-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup>
</p><p>Conversion factors:
</p>
<ul><li>1&nbsp;Ci =3D <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"70103=
70000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>3.7<span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin=
-right:0.15em;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>10</sup>&nbsp;Bq</span> =3D 37&nbsp;GBq=
</li>
<li>1&nbsp;=CE=BCCi =3D <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"700=
4370000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>37<span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">000<=
/span>&nbsp;Bq</span> =3D 37&nbsp;kBq</li>
<li>1&nbsp;Bq =3D <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"699999900=
0000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>2.7<span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-rig=
ht:0.15em;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>=E2=88=9211</sup>&nbsp;Ci</span> =3D <span =
class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"6999999000000000000=E2=99=A0"></s=
pan>2.7<span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em;">=C3=97</span=
>10<sup>=E2=88=925</sup>&nbsp;=CE=BCCi</span></li>
<li>1&nbsp;MBq =3D 0.027&nbsp;mCi</li></ul>
